Diagnosis.
D. lesserti
is very similar to
D. validior
, but can be distinguished by its much smaller terminal embolar apophysis (
Fig. 51
), more curved forward, greatly enlarged distally, but with a membranous denticulation, sometimes minute, emerging from its centre (
Fig. 57
), by its wider atrium (
Table 1
), transverse oval ( Figs 49, 53 ) or subtriangular (
Fig. 55
), and the shape of the membranous coils, attenuated distally (
Figs 50, 54, 56
).
